pros:
Colleagues are very nice to each other;
You can learn a lot from your job;
Great work life balance.

Lots of trainings, good collaboration in and among teams in general;
Good benefits including stakeholder profit sharing program, 401k match
The company is very stable

cons:
@MathWorks HYD office: Senior management at the HYD office is the worst. Neither they respect nor recognize hard work. They show a lot of favouritism. Unrealistic deadlines, no proper planning, and they indirectly force people to work long hours by loading them with more work in a short period of time. They do a lot of micro management. Many of the managers show bad attitude and are not at all supportive or empathetic towards their team members. The managers lack professional ethics and any administration skills. 
Well, HYD office was a startup at HYD acquired by MathWorks. This is definitely one of the worst decisions that the CEO has made. The sr.management at HYD office don't lead by example. They maintain the "do as I say" mentality. They advertise MathWorks core values but never follow. It never reflects in their day-to-day activities.

Be it be any company outtings or providing snacks, milk, and beverages to the employees, they always buy the cheaper ones in the market and doesn't care about the quality of the items that they buy and how it impacts an individual's health.

pros:
Good management team;
Sufficient down time;
Stable company with not a lot of layoffs lingering;
Pretty good product to contribute to;
Very good benefits and >50% 401k match a 100% of the time;
Eventual growth.

All in all, this is a great company to work for, if you plan to stay for at least 5-6 years, not a company that can grant instant gratification.

cons:
Pace to market is very slow compared to industry standards, since the product is still primarily a desktop product. Updates cannot be pushed at a brisk pace;

Pay might be substandard for the first couple of years given that the Boston suburbs are pretty damn expensive;

Behind the curve on industry standard in web services development;

Products are not as diverse as one would expect them to be, however that trend seems to be changing fast;

Changing teams not as easy as it should be.
